trend_summary: Built-up fabric gradually expands outward from the highway corridor, with scattered infill converting tree cover to housing and commercial blocks. Road network becomes denser, yet extensive woodland and lakes persist, keeping green cover dominant. Overall change reflects steady suburbanisation rather than dramatic urban sprawl.
notable_changes: Progressive infill of vacant parcels north and south of the east-west highway.
New residential subdivisions appear in the south-central sector, reducing forest patches.
Commercial/industrial footprints enlarge near major interchanges, visible as larger white roofs.
Local road grid widens, adding connectors that knit previously isolated cul-de-sacs.
Tree canopy thins along water edges, suggesting park development or trail installation.
